rmk:
This recording was made in Turkey in early summer, in a garden located between apartment buildings. The area includes fig trees (Ficus carica) and tree-of-heaven (Ailanthus altissima), providing medium to tall canopy for perching.

The bird was not seen. The vocalization is very clear and flute-like, repeated several times as "fifi fi, fifi fi, fifi fiiuu", with a descending pitch at the end. The recording has excellent clarity (Quality A), with little to no background noise.

Recording is unmodified except for light normalization; no filtering or cutting was applied.

Behavior: The bird sings only a few times per day, each session lasting about 2–3 minutes. This audio captures one of those rare vocalizations. No other individuals were interacting, and there was no visual contact.

Weather: Clear sky, mild temperature, low wind. Recorded in the early morning.

Background species may be present but not clearly identifiable.

Any help in identifying this species is welcome.

[SNR:](https://xeno-canto.org/article/275) 62 dB(ISO/ITU)

**Recorded:** song: characteristically loud, sharp, and somewhat metallic, *tsi-tsi-daa tsi-tsi-daa*

**Area and habitat:** Mixed forest grows along a gently sloping hillside, close to a bay. 

**Bird observations:** The Great Tit can be heard singing from the edge of the forest. 

**Weather conditions:** Clear skies. Temperature: 4°C/39°F. Calm.

**Sound classification and rendering:** Cramp, S. and Perrins, C. M. (ed.) (1993) *The Birds of the Western Palearctic, Volume 7: Flycatchers to Shrikes.* Oxford University Press, Oxford.

**Other distinguishable species:** European Greenfinch,*Chloris chlors*, flight call, at e.g. 0:00.6; Common Wood Pigeon, *Columba palumbus*, song, at e.g. 0:11.1 (vaguely); European Robin, *Erithacus rubecula*, song, at e.g. 0:22; Song Thrush, *Turdus philomelos*, song, at e.g. 0:23.6; Eurasian Treecreeper, *Certhia familiaris*, call, at e.g. 0:45.8.

[SNR:](https://xeno-canto.org/article/275) 63 dB(ISO/ITU)

**Recorded:** foreground bird: song, characteristically loud, sharp, and somewhat metallic; an aberrant four-note stanza, *tsi-tsi-da-ti tsi-tsi-da-ti*, at e.g. 0:01, 0:08.4 and 0:24.7; background bird: churring call, *chich-ich-ich-ich-ich*, at 0:14.5, 0:22 and 0:23.5. 

**Area and habitat:** conifers grow on rocky ground by a bay. 

**Bird observations:** a male Great tit sings from a pine tree. 

**Sound classification and rendering:**  Cramp, S. and Perrins, C. M. (ed.) (1993) *The Birds of the Western Palearctic, Volume 7: Flycatchers to Shrikes.* Oxford University Press, Oxford.

**Other distinguishable species:** Eurasian Blue Tit *Cyanistes caeruleus*, churring call at e.g. 0:03.8 and 0:10.4; Goldcrest *Regulus regulus*, song at e.g. 0:04.4; Common Reed Bunting *Emberiza schoeniclus*, call at e.g. 0:16.9 (vaguely).

continuation from XC351439:
The Tit sings 5 other types of verses (Strophentypen nach Bergmann) with changing motives, rhythm and pitches (Tonhöhen)
4 – fourth type of verse: 50 verses,  to 5:27, each verse with nearly the same motive 3-9 times repeated (mostly, 23x, 6 times)  
5 – fifth type of verse : 66 verses, from 5:21 to 11:24, each verse with the same motive, which is similar to a Coal Tit's song,   1- 9 times repeated (mostly, 29x, 6 times)
6 – sixth type of verse: from 11:25 to 11:50, only 3 verses  
7 – seventh type of verse: from 12:02 to 12:14, only 4 verses. At 12:11 only one motive, similar to the second type (in XC351439)
12:15 alarm call
8 – eigth type of verse: from 12:20 to 12:52, each verse with nearly the same motive, 7 times repeated.
From 5:28 a second Great Tit in the background begins to answer.
At least the Tit flies into a garden with a lot of trees, where I cannot see it all the time, so I am not sure, if the last 3 types of verses have been sung by one individuum, or,  if one ore two types have been sung from a second individuum, coming into the foreground.

the Tit sings 3 types of verses (Strophentypen nach Bergmann) with changing motives, rhythm and pitches (Tonhöhen)
1- first type of verse: only 5 verses, because the Tit`s singing was in full swing, when I began to record
2 – second type of verse: 57 verses, from 0:39 to 6:04, each verse with the same motive 3-8 times repeated (mostly, 30x, 5 times)
3 – third type of verse: 60 verses, from 6: 07 to 11:31, each verse with the same motive, 3-6 times repeated (mostly, 42x, 4 times).

AUDACITY : Repris d'un rush où j'ai ôté tous les artefacts et espacement trop longs sans bruits de lutte.

CIRCONSTANCES DE L'ENREGISTREMENT - COMPORTEMENT : un mâle lance le petit trill qu'on entend à plusieurs reprises. Il est dans un arbre, à quelque 10 m peut-être. Lorsque je le repère, il y a un autre oiseau (mésange charbonnière femelle). Le mâle se rapproche de moi, toujours avec ce cri (inquiétude ou contact avec la femelle ?). Arrivé à hauteur de l'entrée du nichoir, attaché à ce même arbre, il s'arrête et poursuit ses cris. La femelle approche mais est peu visible. Lui, il fait le va-et-vient de son perchoir au nichoir. Il s'accroche près de l'entrée et regarde parfois à l'intérieur. A un moment donné, il chante à deux reprises. Il va ensuite entrer dans le nichoir et en ressortir assez vite. La femelle va s'envoler et lui va la suivre. Ma présence dérangeait-elle (immobile avec mon enregistreur) ou la femelle (qui a mauvais goût) n'aime pas le nichoir que j'ai installé ?

loc: Park on the outskirts of Dubna, Moscow region
rmk:
The recording was made in a large park on the outskirts of a small town, about 50-100 m from the banks of a minor river (more like a creek, really). Forest around the site of recording consist mostly of pines, spruce and  black alder. The bird itself wasn't seen but judging by the direction of the sound, it was somewhere high up in the canopy of a large spruce tree (about 20-25 m off the ground). Weather conditions at the time of recording - no precipitation, almost no wind, overcast skies, temperature around -10 C. 
The recording posted here was extracted from a video and trimmed to remove initial segment without the bird's voice. There is a bit of background noise from the nearby road but the bird's voice is heard quite clearly.
P.S. After some discussion in forum this recording was attributed to *Parus major* with a possible call of *Garrulus glandarius* in the background.

rmk: Two different songs

The recording was made on a mobile phone and amplified digitally to increase the audibility of the call. There have been several great tits _(Parus major)_ in the immediate area throughout the day, and while I've never heard a great tit sound quite like the call in the recording, it is possible that the perpetrator is just an unusual great tit. However, I thought it was interesting and wanted to be sure. I've heard this particular call throughout the day, and have been unable to spot the bird making it. The area is suburban, and less than a hundred metres from a small patch of woodland. There are several large beech trees lining the road, and the bird seemed to be calling from one close by, though I wasn't able to spot it from my window, and therefore I assume the bird was rather small.

The weather was warm and sunny today, about 20 degrees centigrade, and there was little wind.



Edit: The bird appeared in full view the next day and was, in fact, a male common blackbird _(Turdus merula merula)._ Curious to know if anyone else has heard a blackbird make a similar call.

Calls from a Great Tit (a first-winter male). When first heard from indoors the call sounded like that of a Yellow-browed Warbler. The date - 25th September - was fine for an early Yellow-browed Warbler in Ireland so I rushed out into my garden. The calls kept coming from high up in alder trees and I then raced back indoors to fetch my recorder. I set the recorder down and then scanned to locate the bird. Soon I saw it and also watched it call. It was a Great Tit, a young male! It went quiet and then flew off. Two questions arise: if, as I think, the call is a good copy of Yellow-browed Warbler, had the Great Tit heard the real thing recently? Because it was a young bird, it could not have remembered if from a previous year. If the Great Tit did copy a real Yellow-browed Warbler then the Great Tit might itself have travelled to my garden in northeastern Ireland from, say, Yorkshire where it heard Yellow-browed Warblers recently (over 100 Yellow-browed Warblers at Flamborough Head, Yorkshire, a few days ago). Here is a real Yellow-browed XC198000. The upsweep in the second syllable is quite similar in the Great Tit's first and last note.

Parte 1 de 2. Uno de los audios de carbonero más diverso que he grabado, incluyendo imitación de Cyanistes Caeruleus y Cyanopica Cooki. Dos ejemplares, posiblemente pareja. El ecosistema consiste en un cauce de un arroyo seco rodeado por un mosaico de ecosistemas muy diversos. Gran parte de la vegetación riparia ha sido eliminada por los agricultores pero todavía existena lgunas zonas con enormes álamos, tarays y carrizo. Más allá una mezcla de eriales, pinares, bosques de quercíneas, viñedos y alguna granja. Fruto de la sobreexplotación agraria los acuíferos están agotados por lo cual el arroyo madre actualmente va seco, pero ahy un pequeño cauce que sí lleva algo del preciado líquido y que está densamente rodeado de zarzas, álamos, etc. Ahí oculté una de mis grabadoras para rcoger el sonido de cualquier pájaro que pasara por allí.

En este parque se ha utilizado casi exclusivamente vegetación autóptona y además se ha aprovechado el curso del cercano río Guadalquivir para hacer dos lagunas en él. Por estos motivos y por su influencia fluvial este parque tiene una gran diversidad ornitológica.

rmk: El paraje es un bosque mediterráneo con pinos, quercíneas y matorral variado con suelo montañoso y agreste. Cerca hay un río y un pantano y un túnel de una vía de tren avandonada.

Esta universidad cuenta con un campus muy rico en biodiversidad ya que es un pequeño mosaico de ecosistemas. Dispone de dos pequeñas lagunas irrigadas por el llamado Canal de los presos. Además tiene un bosquete de pinos, una zona adehesada con árboles variados incluídos Ficus, Morus, populus, Arbutus, Olea, y una zona de pastizal abierto. los mismos edificios al estar rodeados de naturaleza también son un hábiytat en sí mismos. La Sociedad Española de Ornitología ha montado allí una delegación y hay diversos proyectos de alumnos y profesores relacionados con la naturaleza.

loc: observatorio del acebrón, el rocío, huelva, andalucía
rmk: Tanto el observatorio de la Rocina como el del Alcebrón tienen un ecosistema parecido, salvo que en este último hay un palacio del primer tercio del siglo XX que la gente también va a visitar. Ambos lugares están bastante preparados, tienen observatorios para aves en las lagunas, puentes en los arroyos y caminos de tablas para un cómodo desplazamiento de los observadores. El ecosistema es bosque de pino y encina, en la Rocina predominan los primeros mientras que en el Alcebrón las segundas, alternados con lagunas y arroyos que se secan en verano y que están jalonados de vegetación palustre y de ribera tal como todo tipo de carrizos y juncos, árboles típicos de ribera, cañas y helechos. Lo cierto es que algo que llama la atención es que tanto en un bosque como en otro el arbolado está más enfermo de lo que debería, pues los pinos tienen mucho ramaje seco y se ven bastantes encinas muertas.

Imitación bastante perfecta de la llamada de Fringilla Coelebs. El hábitat es bastante peculiar con bosques en los que se encuentran varias especies de quercíneas alternados con cultivos de castaño. El sotobosque es muy variado y entre las especies con que cuenta están los helechos. Ello se debe a la altura de esta serranía, a la abundancia de cursos de agua y a la influencia atlántica del clima.

rmk: Imitación de Passer Domesticus. En este lugar se realizan actividades de caza y ganadería a la par que es utilizado como lugar de esparcimiento por los autóptonos. Además es un espacio valioso para la fauna y allí se encuentra la mayor colonia de cigueña blanca sobre acebuche. El hábitat consta de un gran pinar, un bosque adehesado de acebuches, un erial y un sistema dulceacuícola compuesto por el arroyo Majaberraque y la laguna donde desemboca.

rmk: I consider this an important example of Great Tit mimicking other species that it knows to be present in its territory and, through copying their voice, intentionally drawing them in to join with the Great Tit in observing a trespasser, predator or anything that the Great Tit regards as worth investigating. In this instance, I am the curiosity. The recording begins (during the first two seconds) with a popular 'pink, pink' refrain that precedes Great Tit's diagnostic 'revving' [please read detailed comments of XC202429 to establish what I mean by 'revving']. The 'pink, pink' seems to function as a copy of the same note commonly used by Chaffinch. At 0:04, the 'pink, pink' is dropped and only revving is uttered. After 0:04 (but closer to the fifth second) a faint Blue Tit call (this tuneful note serves as both song and alarm call) is heard in the background. Just after 0:07, the Great Tit delivers 'pink, pink, pink'. In the following few seconds the Great Tit moved farther off but, at 0:11, it prefaces revving with the trill of a Long-tailed Tit. Indeed, Long-tailed Tits were in the immediate area and, shortly after, both they and more Blue and Coal Tits all appeared like rats responding to the summons of the 'Pied Piper' Great Tit.

This recording contains calls from both Great Tit and Blue Tit. Therefore, the same recording has been added to XC for Blue Tit at XC202479. The text (repeated from XC202479) applies equally to Great Tit: 'Blue Tit delivering its standard conversational trill (I prefer to call the sound 'revving'). This is a year-round call and is quite similar to an equivalent vocalisation in Great Tit. For more detailed discussion see [Great Tit] XC202429 and [Blue Tit] XC202431. The Blue Tit revving is recorded only within the first two seconds. At 0:04 a Great Tit delivers a single Dunnock-like 'peep' and does so again at 0:06 at which moment is then switches immediately to include its diagnostic revving. Hence, the recording facilitates hearing - and comparing - revving from both Blue Tit (within the first two seconds) and Great Tit (0:07).'

Great Tits are renowned for the complexity of their vocabulary. Indeed, the more you immerse yourself in their language the more you appreciate the bird's communication skills. While it is exciting and a privilege to listen to everything they say, the result is that you begin to feel like a code-breaker - and this obliges you to take notes of the various sounds and permutations of sounds. Clearly, one recording on Xeno-canto is not going to serve as a Rosetta stone for deciphering the meaning of every utterance! Nonetheless, one standard sound is given by Great Tit and Blue Tit. The utterance is quite similar in both species and seems to be a constant feature in their phraseology throughout the year. Consequently, an ability to distinguish the two on the basis of the sound is very useful. To my mind, the vocalisation comes across as a kind of 'revving'. In Great Tit, the revving is homogeneous - flat without any change in pitch. And it ends just as it began. So its sheer 'sameness' is, in fact, distinctive. The revving of Blue Tit is different in two ways. On the one hand it rises slightly in pitch [XC202431] and also seems to accelerate a little. But back to Great Tit. Often Great Tit prefaces its revving with (usually single) another note. The prefaced note may be unique to Great Tit or it may instead be a copy of other species that the Great Tit knows to be present in the area. By imitating the note from its neighbours it may be copying 'for fun' or to alert its neighbours to the fact that it has rumbled something interesting or alarming, such as perceived danger in the form of a human trespasser, stalking cat or other predator. The intention behind copying may not be altruistic but could be to imitate the other species so precisely that individuals may join the Great Tit - because they believe that the sound has, in reality, emanated from one of their peers. In Ireland, the two species imitated most in this way are Chaffinch and Dunnock. In the recording, no species is imitated before revving. However, a high-pitched 'air-escaping-from-piston' sound (that can be matched by a very similar sound in Blue Tit's repertoire) is given either on its own [just after 0:10] 
or - in classic fashion - by being added as a preface to revving. The 'piston' note is combined with revving just after 0:21, just after 0:25, 0:31, 0:34 and 0:37. In total, 20 sound bites are uttered in the course of this recording. For the record these are: over the first 10 seconds, a total of 5 'revving' bursts; the sixth note is a piston sound; sound bites 7, 8 and 9 are revving; sound bite 10 is a piston prefacing revving; 11 and 12 are revving only; 13 is a piston prefacing revving; 14 and 15 are revving only; 16 is piston prefacing revving; 17 is revving; 18 is piston prefacing revving; 19 is revving; 20 is piston prefacing revving. Another recording featuring revving from both Great Tit and Blue Tit is XC202479.

rmk: Smallish (10-15 cm long), brownish with a definitely lighter color belly, shortish tail. Saw it hiding in the canopy, perched on a high branch. In the area there are numerous Fringilla coelebs, Turdus merula and various other songbirds. I stayed underneath the tree, tracking its position, waiting to get a chance at a better look, but after a couple minutes it quickly flew off to another tree farther away. Could it be a Parus major?
